{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774409178,"nonce":"vybQjiHMTjp0qLSUGM3yu7ggABo=","message":"**Adversary network design notes**\n\nOpen-loop adversary inputs: The adversary should receive the reach vector (target - start position), not absolute target position, plus SISU. This ensures the adversary's strategy is translation-invariant, matching the point-mass dynamics.\n\nClosed-loop adversary timing: A GRU-based adversary doesn't need discrete timing decisions. It outputs continuous force at every timestep, but training naturally produces sparse, burst-like output patterns because concentrated force at the optimal moment is more disruptive than distributed force. The \"when to strike\" decision emerges from the continuous optimization.\n\nBayesian adversary: An ensemble of K parameterized adversaries (different initializations, trained in parallel) approximates a posterior over worst-case perturbation strategies. This gives distributions over perturbation timing/magnitude rather than point estimates. More compute-intensive but more informative.","files":null}]}